<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-18T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-18T08:00:00-05:00" n="657" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d657">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">394.115 Panay/154: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Hankow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-18T21:00:00+08:00">December 18, 1937—9
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received December 18—4:15 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>86. Following from Commander-in-Chief: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“0018. Boarding boat was Japanese motor launch, 40 feet long,
                                    engine amidships, light machine gun in bow protected by steel
                                    shields. Boat’s sides planking of clinker construction. Boat
                                    contained approximately 20 Japanese soldiers, boarding officers
                                    name previously reported to you by <hi rend="italic">Panay</hi>.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <p>Sent to Department. Repeated to Peiping and Shanghai. Peiping repeat to
                            Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>